        {
          t: 'Deque Problems',
          learn: '<div class="learn-section"><div class="learn-h">1. Why This Matters</div><p class="learn-p">The <b>deque</b> (double-ended queue) is the workhorse behind sliding window problems&mdash;one of the most common interview categories. <b>Sliding window maximum</b> appears in real-time data streaming, financial analytics (rolling max/min), and network packet scheduling. Understanding the monotonic deque technique lets you solve these in O(n) instead of O(nk). The <code>std::deque</code> is also the default underlying container for both <code>std::stack</code> and <code>std::queue</code> in C++, making it foundational knowledge.</p></div><div class="learn-section"><div class="learn-h">2. Core Concept</div><p class="learn-p">A <b>deque</b> (Double-Ended Queue) supports insertion and removal at both ends in <span class="learn-complexity">O(1)</span> time.</p><div class="learn-code">#include &lt;deque&gt;\ndeque&lt;int&gt; dq;\ndq.push_back(1);    // [1]\ndq.push_front(0);   // [0, 1]\ndq.push_back(2);    // [0, 1, 2]\ndq.pop_front();     // [1, 2]\ndq.pop_back();      // [1]\ndq.front();         // 1\ndq.back();          // 1\ndq[0];              // 1 (random access!)</div><p class="learn-p"><b>Internal Implementation:</b> <code>std::deque</code> is NOT a circular buffer. It is a sequence of <b>fixed-size memory blocks</b> connected by a <b>map</b> (array of block pointers).</p><div class="learn-code">std::deque internal structure:\n\n map[]: [ptr0] [ptr1] [ptr2] [ptr3]\n           |      |      |      |\n           v      v      v      v\n        [block] [block] [block] [block]\n         (each block holds ~512/sizeof(T) elements)\n\n push_front: add to front of first block (or allocate new block)\n push_back:  add to back of last block (or allocate new block)\n operator[]: two pointer dereferences (block lookup + offset)</div></div><div class="learn-section"><div class="learn-h">3. Building Blocks</div><table class="learn-table"><tr><th>Operation</th><th>deque</th><th>vector</th><th>list</th></tr><tr><td>push_front</td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(1)</span></td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(n)</span></td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(1)</span></td></tr><tr><td>push_back</td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(1)</span> amortized</td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(1)</span> amortized</td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(1)</span></td></tr><tr><td>pop_front</td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(1)</span></td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(n)</span></td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(1)</span></td></tr><tr><td>pop_back</td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(1)</span></td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(1)</span></td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(1)</span></td></tr><tr><td>Random access</td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(1)</span></td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(1)</span></td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(n)</span></td></tr><tr><td>Insert in middle</td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(n)</span></td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(n)</span></td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(1)</span></td></tr></table><p class="learn-p">Deque is a hybrid: O(1) at both ends like a list, plus O(1) random access like a vector. This is why it is the default for both stack and queue.</p></div><div class="learn-section"><div class="learn-h">4. Working Through It</div><p class="learn-p"><b>Dry run: Sliding Window Maximum on [1, 3, -1, -3, 5, 3, 6, 7], k=3</b></p><div class="learn-code">Deque stores indices in decreasing order of values.\n\ni=0 (1):  dq=[]     push 0        dq=[0(1)]\ni=1 (3):  3&gt;1, pop 0. push 1      dq=[1(3)]\ni=2 (-1): -1&lt;3, push 2            dq=[1(3),2(-1)]\n          i&gt;=k-1: result=[3]      (front=idx 1, val=3)\ni=3 (-3): -3&lt;-1, push 3           dq=[1(3),2(-1),3(-3)]\n          i&gt;=k-1: result=[3,3]    (front=idx 1, val=3)\ni=4 (5):  front=1, 1 &lt; 4-3+1=2, pop front\n          5&gt;-3, pop 3. 5&gt;-1, pop 2. push 4\n                                    dq=[4(5)]\n          result=[3,3,5]\ni=5 (3):  3&lt;5, push 5              dq=[4(5),5(3)]\n          result=[3,3,5,5]\ni=6 (6):  6&gt;3, pop 5. 6&gt;5, pop 4. push 6\n                                    dq=[6(6)]\n          result=[3,3,5,5,6]\ni=7 (7):  7&gt;6, pop 6. push 7       dq=[7(7)]\n          result=[3,3,5,5,6,7]\n\nFinal result: [3, 3, 5, 5, 6, 7]</div></div><div class="learn-section"><div class="learn-h">5. Patterns &amp; Variations</div><ul class="learn-list"><li><b>Sliding Window Maximum:</b> Monotonic decreasing deque of indices. Pop from back when current &gt; back. Pop from front when out of window. Front is always the max.</li><li><b>Sliding Window Minimum:</b> Same technique, flip comparison. Monotonic increasing deque.</li><li><b>Shortest Subarray with Sum &gt;= K (with negatives):</b> Use prefix sums + monotonic deque. This is harder than the two-pointer version because negative numbers prevent simple sliding window.</li><li><b>Max of All Subarrays of Size K:</b> Same as sliding window maximum.</li><li><b>Constrained Subsequence Sum:</b> DP + sliding window maximum optimization.</li></ul><div class="learn-code">vector&lt;int&gt; maxSlidingWindow(vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; nums, int k) {\n    deque&lt;int&gt; dq;\n    vector&lt;int&gt; result;\n    for (int i = 0; i &lt; (int)nums.size(); i++) {\n        // Remove out-of-window indices\n        while (!dq.empty() &amp;&amp; dq.front() &lt; i - k + 1)\n            dq.pop_front();\n        // Maintain decreasing order\n        while (!dq.empty() &amp;&amp; nums[dq.back()] &lt; nums[i])\n            dq.pop_back();\n        dq.push_back(i);\n        if (i &gt;= k - 1)\n            result.push_back(nums[dq.front()]);\n    }\n    return result;\n}</div></div><div class="learn-section"><div class="learn-h">6. Pitfalls &amp; Edge Cases</div><div class="learn-warn"><b>Common Bugs:</b></div><ul class="learn-list"><li><b>Expiry check order:</b> Always check and remove expired indices from the front BEFORE processing the current element. Otherwise you might return an expired maximum.</li><li><b>Window size 1:</b> Every element is its own window maximum/minimum. The deque always has exactly one element.</li><li><b>All elements equal:</b> The deque fills up to size k. No pops from the back, only expiry from the front.</li><li><b>Sorted ascending input:</b> Each push pops all previous elements. The deque is always size 1.</li><li><b>Sorted descending input:</b> No pops from the back. The deque fills to size k, and only expires from the front.</li><li><b>Confusing deque with monotonic stack:</b> The deque can expire elements from the front (window constraint). A stack cannot. This is the key difference.</li></ul><div class="learn-tip"><b>Tip:</b> The monotonic deque is essentially a monotonic stack that also supports removal from the front for sliding window expiry. If there is no window constraint, a simple monotonic stack suffices.</div></div><div class="learn-section"><div class="learn-h">7. Complexity &amp; Comparison</div><table class="learn-table"><tr><th>Approach for Sliding Window Max</th><th>Time</th><th>Space</th></tr><tr><td>Brute force</td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(nk)</span></td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(1)</span></td></tr><tr><td>Monotonic deque</td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(n)</span></td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(k)</span></td></tr><tr><td>Max heap (priority queue)</td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(n log k)</span></td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(k)</span></td></tr><tr><td>Segment tree</td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(n log n)</span></td><td><span class="learn-complexity">O(n)</span></td></tr></table><p class="learn-p">The monotonic deque is optimal for sliding window problems. The heap approach is simpler but slower (O(n log k) vs O(n)). The key insight: each element enters and leaves the deque at most once, giving amortized O(1) per element.</p></div><div class="learn-section"><div class="learn-h">8. Interview Spotlight</div><p class="learn-p"><b>Q1: What is the time complexity of sliding window maximum using a deque?</b><br>O(n). Each element is pushed and popped from the deque at most once across all window slides.</p><p class="learn-p"><b>Q2: What order does the monotonic deque maintain for sliding window maximum?</b><br>Decreasing values from front to back. The front always holds the index of the current window\'s maximum.</p><p class="learn-p"><b>Q3: Why is a deque needed instead of a stack for sliding window problems?</b><br>Need to remove expired elements from the front (which left the window). A stack only allows removal from the top (back).</p><p class="learn-p"><b>Q4: Why does std::stack and std::queue both use deque by default?</b><br>Stack needs push_back/pop_back (deque: O(1)). Queue needs push_back/pop_front (deque: O(1)). Vector can\'t do pop_front in O(1). Deque handles both patterns efficiently.</p><p class="learn-p"><b>Q5: How is std::deque different from a circular buffer?</b><br>A circular buffer is a fixed-size array with wraparound. std::deque uses multiple fixed-size blocks connected by a pointer map, allowing dynamic growth at both ends.</p><p class="learn-p"><b>Q6: How would you find the median of a sliding window?</b><br>Use two heaps (max-heap for lower half, min-heap for upper half) or a multiset with a middle iterator. This is harder than max/min and is O(n log k).</p></div>',
          code: `#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <deque>
using namespace std;

// ---- Sliding Window Maximum ----
vector<int> maxSlidingWindow(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
    deque<int> dq; // indices in decreasing order of values
    vector<int> result;
    for (int i = 0; i < (int)nums.size(); i++) {
        // Remove out-of-window indices
        while (!dq.empty() && dq.front() < i - k + 1)
            dq.pop_front();
        // Maintain decreasing order
        while (!dq.empty() && nums[dq.back()] < nums[i])
            dq.pop_back();
        dq.push_back(i);
        if (i >= k - 1)
            result.push_back(nums[dq.front()]);
    }
    return result;
}

// ---- Sliding Window Minimum ----
vector<int> minSlidingWindow(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
    deque<int> dq;
    vector<int> result;
    for (int i = 0; i < (int)nums.size(); i++) {
        while (!dq.empty() && dq.front() < i - k + 1)
            dq.pop_front();
        while (!dq.empty() && nums[dq.back()] > nums[i])
            dq.pop_back();
        dq.push_back(i);
        if (i >= k - 1)
            result.push_back(nums[dq.front()]);
    }
    return result;
}

// ---- Max of all subarrays of size k (same as sliding window max) ----
void printMaxOfSubarrays(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
    auto result = maxSlidingWindow(nums, k);
    cout << "Max of subarrays (k=" << k << "): ";
    for (int x : result) cout << x << " ";
    cout << endl;
}

// ---- Deque basic operations demo ----
void dequeDemo() {
    deque<int> dq;
    dq.push_back(10);
    dq.push_back(20);
    dq.push_front(5);
    dq.push_front(1);
    // dq = [1, 5, 10, 20]

    cout << "Deque: ";
    for (int x : dq) cout << x << " ";
    cout << endl;

    cout << "Front: " << dq.front() << ", Back: " << dq.back() << endl;
    cout << "dq[2]: " << dq[2] << endl; // random access

    dq.pop_front(); // remove 1
    dq.pop_back();  // remove 20
    cout << "After pops: ";
    for (int x : dq) cout << x << " ";
    cout << endl; // 5 10
}

int main() {
    dequeDemo();

    vector<int> nums = {1, 3, -1, -3, 5, 3, 6, 7};
    int k = 3;

    auto maxResult = maxSlidingWindow(nums, k);
    cout << "Sliding max: ";
    for (int x : maxResult) cout << x << " ";
    cout << endl; // 3 3 5 5 6 7

    auto minResult = minSlidingWindow(nums, k);
    cout << "Sliding min: ";
    for (int x : minResult) cout << x << " ";
    cout << endl; // -1 -3 -3 -3 3 3

    return 0;
}`,
          problems: [
            ['Sliding Window Maximum', 'https://leetcode.com/problems/sliding-window-maximum/', 'Hard'],
            ['Shortest Subarray with Sum at Least K', 'https://leetcode.com/problems/shortest-subarray-with-sum-at-least-k/', 'Hard'],
            ['Design Circular Deque', 'https://leetcode.com/problems/design-circular-deque/', 'Medium'],
            ['Longest Continuous Subarray With Absolute Diff <= K', 'https://leetcode.com/problems/longest-continuous-subarray-with-absolute-diff-less-than-or-equal-to-limit/', 'Medium'],
            ['Constrained Subsequence Sum', 'https://leetcode.com/problems/constrained-subsequence-sum/', 'Hard']
          ],
          mcqs: [
            {q: 'What is the time complexity of the sliding window maximum using a deque?', o: ['O(n * k)', 'O(n log k)', 'O(n)', 'O(k)'], a: 2},
            {q: 'What order does the monotonic deque maintain for sliding window maximum?', o: ['Increasing values from front to back', 'Decreasing values from front to back', 'Sorted by index only', 'No particular order'], a: 1},
            {q: 'Why is a deque needed instead of a stack for sliding window problems?', o: ['Deques are faster', 'Need to remove expired elements from the front', 'Stacks cannot store indices', 'No particular reason'], a: 1},
            {q: 'What is the default underlying container for std::stack and std::queue?', o: ['vector', 'list', 'deque', 'array'], a: 2},
            {q: 'How does std::deque achieve O(1) random access?', o: ['It uses a single contiguous array', 'It computes block index and offset within the block', 'It uses a hash table', 'It uses a balanced BST'], a: 1},
            {q: 'What is the space complexity of the deque in sliding window maximum?', o: ['O(1)', 'O(k) where k is window size', 'O(n)', 'O(n*k)'], a: 1}
          ]
        }
